Config maps, secrets, and environment.

What is covered. This notebook walks through the configuration problem — why baking config into an image is a dead end. The config map — kubernetes' first-class object for non-sensitive configuration, with key-value pairs or whole files as values. Three ways to consume a config map — env, env from, and as files via a volume mount. Update propagation — env vars are baked at pod start, while volume-mounted config maps live-refresh, with one caveat involving sub path. Immutable config maps and secrets — opting out of updates for fewer kube-let wakeups. Secrets — the same shape as a config map, but for sensitive data, with base64 encoding which is not encryption, and encryption at rest in et-see-dee. Built-in secret types — opaque, kubernetes dot eye-o slash docker config j-son, kubernetes dot eye-o slash tee-el-ess, and a few others. Image pull secrets — how the kube-let authenticates to private registries. And the downward ay-pee-eye — exposing pod metadata, such as name, namespace, eye-pee, labels, and resource limits, to the container as env vars or files.

By the end of this notebook you should be able to externalise application config from container images, inject the same config map and secret in two or three different ways, and know exactly when changing a config map will and will not make it into a running pod. Notebooks two and three are the prerequisites. You should be comfortable writing pod and deployment manifests, because every consumption pattern in this notebook lives inside spec dot containers.

The configuration problem.

You finished notebook three with a deployment running an image. That image bakes in a default config. Now you want to do three things. Run the same image in staging with log level set to debug, and in prod with log level set to warn. Point the web pod at the ay-pee-eye service hostname, but keep the u-r-l configurable so you can swap to a different backend later. And mount the same tee-el-ess certificate into three different services without copying it into three different images.

A few options that do not work in production.

Bake it into the image. You would build a separate image per environment. Now web colon staging and web colon prod are different images with different test coverage. Promotion becomes "build a new image" instead of "redeploy the same image with different config" — which means the image you tested in staging is not the image you ship to prod.

Pass it on the docker run command line. That is where you came from in the docker repo. But pods are launched by the kube-let from a template in et-see-dee, not by you on the command line. Putting dash dash env log level equals warn directly in every deployment is fine for one variable. With twenty variables, every deployment yaml becomes a wall of env entries.

Stash it in a sidecar. Sometimes the right answer, but heavy for "put a value in an env var."

What you really want is a first-class kubernetes object that holds configuration data, lives in the cluster like every other object, and gets referenced from pod templates. Two such objects exist. The config map for non-sensitive data, and the secret for sensitive data. They have nearly identical schemas and consumption patterns. The differences are about handling — base64 storage, encryption at rest, are-back defaults — more than about shape. Master the config map, and the secret is the same thing plus a security posture.

The config map.

A config map is a key-value store of configuration data, scoped to a namespace, that pods reference by name. The values can be short strings or whole files. A typical config map has a name in its metadata, then a data section with keys like log level set to info, greeting set to "hello from staging," and an app properties key whose value is a multi-line block of property assignments.

Two sections under the top level. Data is for string values. Keys are arbitrary. Values are you-tee-f-eight strings — no binary. Most config maps you will ever write live here. Binary data is for base64-encoded binary blobs — for things that are not strings, such as a dot j-k-s keystore, or an image. Less common.

A config map is just data. It has no spec and no status — there is nothing for a controller to reconcile. The cluster does nothing with a config map until a pod references it.

Size limit. A config map, and a secret, is capped at one mebibyte total. This is an et-see-dee limit — every kubernetes object has to fit in one et-see-dee value. For larger configuration, such as a ten megabyte lookup table, put it in object storage, a database, or a sidecar. Not a config map.

Three ways to consume a config map.

A config map on its own does nothing. A pod uses it in one, or more, of three ways.

First, as individual env vars, using env dot value from dot config map key ref. Pull one key out of one config map into one env var. Most precise, most explicit. Use this when you want to rename a key — log level in the config map, but logging level root in the container — or when you only want a subset of a config map's keys.

Second, as a bulk env import, using env from dot config map ref. Slurp every key-value pair from a config map into env vars, with the key as the variable name. Use this when the config map's keys are already your env-var names. Add an optional prefix to namespace them — prefix a-p-p underscore makes log level become a-p-p underscore log level.

Third, as files in a volume, using volume dot config map. Mount the config map as a directory. Each key becomes a file. The file's contents are the value. Perfect for "the app reads slash e-t-c slash app slash config dot yaml." Optional items lets you project only specific keys, rename them, and set the file mode. The volume-mount form is the right choice when the application reads a file — most java virtual machine apps, anything that uses dash dash config followed by a path.

Picking between them. If the app reads env vars and you want a few specific ones, use env with config map key ref. If it reads many env vars from a single source, use env from. If it reads a configuration file, use a volume mount. And if config needs to live-update without a pod restart, use a volume mount — which is the next topic.

Update propagation — env vars versus volume mounts.

The big practical difference between the three consumption patterns is what happens when you update the config map.

Env vars are baked in. Both env with config map key ref, and env from, are resolved once, at pod start. The kube-let reads the config map, builds the env block, and exec-s the container. After that, changing the config map does nothing to running pods. To pick up the new value, you have to restart the pod — typically by triggering a rollout, as in notebook three, by bumping an annotation on the deployment's pod template.

Volume-mounted config maps live-update. When a config map is mounted as a volume, the kube-let writes its keys to a small tmp file system directory inside the pod. When the config map changes, the kube-let rewrites those files within roughly a minute — the sync period is tunable. The container sees new file contents without restarting.

This is great — your n-ginx config reloads when you kubectl apply an updated config map. It is also a footgun. Your container has to actually re-read the file. Many apps load config once at startup. The file might be fresh but the application is still using the old values. The standard fixes are — have the app watch the file, with eye-n-o-tify or a periodic re-read. Or trigger a rollout on every config map change, which is a common git-ops pattern, often done with a checksum annotation in the pod template.

The sub path gotcha. A volume mounted with sub path is not live-updated. Sub path mounts a single file from a volume at a target path — for example, mount only n-ginx dot conf into slash e-t-c slash n-ginx slash n-ginx dot conf without clobbering the rest of slash e-t-c slash n-ginx. It is a separate kernel bind mount and the kube-let does not update it.

If you need live updates and want to land a single file in a directory you cannot replace, mount the whole config map somewhere harmless — for example, slash e-t-c slash configs — and have the app read from there. Or use a sidecar to copy the file on changes.

Immutable config maps, and secrets.

By default the kube-let watches every config map a pod mounts, so it can notice changes. On a large cluster, thousands of config maps, times thousands of pods, times thousands of nodes, means a lot of watches.

Setting immutable true on a config map tells the kube-let — this never changes, do not bother watching it. Once you flip the bit, the config map can only be deleted and recreated, not edited.

The same field exists on secrets. Use it for release-versioned config maps where the file is born, deployed, and dies with one release — you never patch it. The typical pattern — ship app config v three alongside deployment web v three, then delete the pair when you tear down that version. Tools like customise and helm can append a hash of the data to the name automatically, so every change effectively creates a new immutable object.

Secrets — like config maps but for sensitive data.

A secret is the same idea as a config map, plus a handful of differences that exist because the data is sensitive.

What is different from a config map. Storage — secret values in yaml use the data field, which is base64-encoded, or the string data field, which is raw but the ay-pee-eye server base64-encodes it before storing. Config map does not bother with base64 for strings. In-memory mounting — when a secret is mounted as a volume, the kube-let puts it on tmp file system, that is r-ay-m and not disk, so it never touches a node's disk. Et-see-dee storage — by default, secret data sits in et-see-dee as base64. Not encrypted. Most production clusters enable an encryption configuration so the ay-pee-eye server encrypts secret data before writing it to et-see-dee. The see-kay-ay expects you to know that this is optional but recommended, and that it is the ay-pee-eye server, not et-see-dee itself, doing the encryption. Are-back defaults — many cluster role definitions exclude secrets from "read everything in this namespace." Treat secrets as more sensitive than config maps by policy, even though the underlying object kind is similar.

Base64 is encoding, not encryption. The single most important fact about secrets is — base64 is not encryption. It is an encoding. Anyone with get secret access can decode it instantly. Pipe the base64 string into base64 dash dee and you get the plaintext back.

If you commit a secret yaml to git — even base64-encoded — you have committed plaintext. The community-standard solutions are sealed secrets, which encrypts so only the in-cluster controller can decrypt. External secrets operator, which syncs from vault, ay-double-you-ess secrets manager, and similar systems. And s-o-p-s, which encrypts the yaml with k-m-s or p-g-p. Out of scope for the see-kay-ay. Standard for production.

Creating secrets.

The same three creation methods as config map, plus a few secret-specific shortcuts.

From literals. Kubectl create secret generic, the name, then dash dash from literal key equals value for each one. From files. Kubectl create secret generic, the name, then dash dash from file followed by a key equals path expression. Handy for binary or large values like a private key. From a tee-el-ess cert and key pair. Kubectl create secret tee-el-ess, the name, dash dash cert followed by the certificate file, and dash dash key followed by the key file. This creates a typed secret with the kubernetes dot eye-o slash tee-el-ess type. From a docker registry credential. Kubectl create secret docker registry, the name, dash dash docker server, dash dash docker username, dash dash docker password, and optionally dash dash docker email.

Declarative form. The yaml shown above, with data or string data. Use string data while you are authoring. The ay-pee-eye server converts it to base64 on write.

Data versus string data precedence. If both are set and a key appears in each, string data wins. Useful when patching.

Consuming secrets.

Identical to config maps. Three ways.

As an env var, using secret key ref. Specify the secret name and the key. The value becomes the env var.

As a bulk env import, using env from with secret ref. Every key in the secret becomes an env var. As with config maps, prefix is supported.

As files in a volume, using volume dot secret. Specify the secret name. Each key becomes a file in the mount path. Two secret-specific volume knobs matter here. Default mode, and items dot mode — file permissions. The default is six-four-four. For sensitive data, prefer four-zero-zero so only the container's user can read. And tmp file system backing. As mentioned above, secret volumes are r-ay-m backed. This is automatic. You do not ask for it.

Update propagation is the same as config maps. Env vars are baked at pod start. Volumes live-refresh.

Do not echo secrets in container logs. Sounds obvious. Bears repeating. The most common secret leak in the wild is echo dollar dee-bee password left in an entry-point script, or a misconfigured spring boot that logs every env var on startup. Pods' standard output streams to node disks and from there to your logging pipeline.

Built-in secret types.

A secret's type field is a hint about what is inside. The cluster does not enforce the schema for most types — it is documentation that some controllers check for.

Common types. Opaque, the default — arbitrary key-value, used for most user secrets. Kubernetes dot eye-o slash service account token — a j-w-t for a service account, auto-created per service account and injected into pods. Kubernetes dot eye-o slash docker cfg — a legacy tilde slash dot docker cfg j-son, used for legacy image pull. Kubernetes dot eye-o slash docker config j-son — a tilde slash dot docker slash config dot j-son blob, used for modern image pull. Kubernetes dot eye-o slash basic auth — with username and password keys. Kubernetes dot eye-o slash s-s-h auth — with an s-s-h private key. Kubernetes dot eye-o slash tee-el-ess — with t-l-s dot c-r-t and t-l-s dot key, used by ingress and webhook servers. And bootstrap dot kubernetes dot eye-o slash token — kube-ay-dee-m join tokens, used during cluster bootstrap.

The two you will create most often. Tee-el-ess secrets. The type is kubernetes dot eye-o slash tee-el-ess. The data has tee-el-ess dot c-r-t and tee-el-ess dot key, each base64 of the p-e-m blob. Easiest to create with kubectl create secret tee-el-ess. Consumed by ingress resources, covered in notebook nine, and by any pod that needs to serve h-t-t-p-s. Image pull secrets, which we cover next.

Image pull secrets.

If your pod runs an image from a private registry, the kube-let on the node needs credentials to pull it. That is what image pull secrets is for.

Step one. Create the credential as a secret. Run kubectl create secret docker registry with a name like reg-cred, then dash dash docker server, dash dash docker username, dash dash docker password. That creates a secret of type kubernetes dot eye-o slash docker config j-son whose data is a base64 of a tilde slash dot docker slash config dot j-son blob.

Step two. Reference it from the pod spec. Add image pull secrets in spec, with a list of secret names. The kube-let uses the secret to authenticate when pulling the image. The secret is only used for image pull. The running container never sees it as an env var or a file.

Cluster-wide alternative — attach to the service account. If every pod in a namespace needs the same registry credential, set it once on the namespace's default service account and skip the per-pod image pull secrets. Use kubectl patch serviceaccount default with a patch that adds image pull secrets. Every pod created in this namespace that does not override the service account now picks up the credential automatically. Service accounts land properly in notebook ten alongside are-back.

The downward ay-pee-eye.

Sometimes the container needs to know something about itself — its own pod name, namespace, eye-pee, node, labels, or resource limits. None of that is in a config map or a secret. It is in the pod's own object, and the downward ay-pee-eye exposes it.

Two surfaces.

As env vars. In the env section of the container, each entry has a name and a value from field ref. Field ref takes a field path like metadata dot name, metadata dot namespace, status dot pod eye-pee, or spec dot node name. There is also resource field ref, which takes a container name, a resource like limits dot see-pee-you, and an optional divisor — for example, one milli for milli-cores.

As files in a volume. A volume of type downward ay-pee-eye lists items, each with a path and a field ref. Mount that volume and the container reads its labels and annotations from files. Useful when an app expects "configuration" but really wants "tell me which environment I am in."

Available fields. Field ref accepts the most-used set — metadata dot name, namespace, you-eye-dee. Metadata dot labels, annotations, or a specific label by key. Spec dot node name and service account name. Status dot host eye-pee, pod eye-pee, and pod eye-pees. Resource field ref accepts limits dot see-pee-you, limits dot memory, limits dot ephemeral storage, and the corresponding requests. Useful for sizing java virtual machine heaps, garbage-collection threads, and the like against actual pod limits.

We already used the downward ay-pee-eye in notebook four — the pod name env var on the h-t-t-p echo deployment came from field ref.

Cleaning up.

Delete everything this notebook created so the cluster is tidy for notebook six. Run kubectl delete pod, followed by the names — c-m consumer, sec consumer, and downward demo. Then kubectl delete config map, followed by app config, app file, and app config yaml. Then kubectl delete secret dee-bee credentials. Or, more bluntly, kubectl delete pod, comma, config map, comma, secret, dash dash all.
